qas.question: Where are laws published after receiving assent?
Where is the original law text stored?

answers.text: in the archives of the King's Offices

qas.question: What happens in the rare case the government doesn't approve of a law that has passed both houses?

answers.text: neither the monarch nor a minister will sign the bill, notifying the States General that "The King will keep the proposal under advisement."

qas.question: The sovereign and two what signs the proposal?
The enabling clause is added to what?

plausible_answers.text: government does not approve a law that has been passed in parliament

qas.question: In what case will the monarch but not the minister sign the bill?
A law that has not received royal assent will be published where?

context: The government, consisting of the monarch and the ministers, will then usually approve <b4_0>the proposal<b4_0/> and the sovereign and one of the <b3_0>ministers<b3_0/> signs the proposal with the addition of an enacting clause, thereafter notifying the States General that "The King assents to the proposal." It has happened in exceptional circumstances that the <b5_0>government does not approve a law that has been passed in parliament<b5_0/>. In such a case, <a2_0>neither the monarch nor a minister will sign the bill, notifying the States General that "The King will keep the proposal under advisement."<a2_0/> A law that has received royal assent will be published in <a0_0>the <b6_0>State Magazine<b6_0/><a0_0/>, with the original being kept <a1_0>in the archives of the King's Offices<a1_0/>.
